 <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mt-16 mb-6">What Is the Main Difference?</h2>
 <p class="mb-6 leading-relaxed">The biggest difference lies in the design of the questions. The TOEFL is almost entirely multiple-choice. You read a text or listen to a lecture and then choose the best answer from four options. This requires a specific type of logic and the ability to eliminate wrong answers quickly.</p>
 <p class="mb-6 leading-relaxed">The IELTS is much more varied. You might have to fill in the blanks of a summary, match headings to paragraphs, or label a diagram. This tests your ability to interact with the language in different ways. Many students find the IELTS more engaging, while others prefer the predictable nature of the TOEFL.</p>

 <div class="bg-blue-900/20 border border-blue-500/30 rounded-2xl p-8 my-12">
 <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Pro Tip: Check Your Target Institution</h3>
 <p class="text-neutral-300">While most universities accept both, some North American schools still prefer the TOEFL, and many UK or Australian institutions lean toward the IELTS. Always check the official requirements of your target university before you start studying.</p>
 </div>

 <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mt-16 mb-6">Comparing the Four Sections</h2>

 <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-10 mb-4">1. Reading</h3>
 <p class="mb-6 leading-relaxed">The TOEFL Reading section uses academic texts. They are similar to what you would find in a first-year university textbook. You will answer 20 questions in about 35 minutes. All questions are multiple-choice.</p>
 <p class="mb-6 leading-relaxed">The IELTS Reading section also uses three long texts. However, the question types change constantly. You might have to decide if a statement is "True, False, or Not Given" or complete a table. This requires you to be very fast at scanning for specific details.</p>

 <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-10 mb-4">2. Listening</h3>
 <p class="mb-6 leading-relaxed">In the TOEFL, you listen to lectures and conversations first, take notes, and then answer the questions. You cannot see the questions while you are listening. This tests your memory and note-taking skills.</p>
 <p class="mb-6 leading-relaxed">In the IELTS, you can see the questions while you listen. You fill in answers as the audio plays. This requires a high level of multi-tasking. You must listen, read, and write at the same time.</p>

 <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-10 mb-4">3. Speaking</h3>
 <p class="mb-6 leading-relaxed">This is where the two exams feel most different. For the TOEFL, you sit in a room with other test-takers and speak into a microphone. You have very strict time limits (usually 45 to 60 seconds per answer). There is no human interaction.</p>
 <p class="mb-6 leading-relaxed">The IELTS Speaking test is a real conversation with a certified examiner. It can take place on a different day than the rest of the test. Many learners find this less stressful because the examiner can repeat questions or clarify points if you are confused.</p>

 <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-10 mb-4">4. Writing</h3>
 <p class="mb-6 leading-relaxed">Both exams have two writing tasks. In the TOEFL, you must type your answers. One task involves reading a text and listening to a lecture, then writing a summary of how they relate. This is called an integrated task.</p>
 <p class="mb-6 leading-relaxed">The IELTS Writing section can be done by hand or on a computer. In the Academic version, you have to describe a visual chart or graph for Task 1. Task 2 is a traditional essay where you argue for or against a specific point of view.</p>

 <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mt-16 mb-6">Which Exam Is Harder?</h2>
 <p class="mb-6 leading-relaxed">Difficulty is subjective. If you are good at multiple-choice and enjoy academic lectures, you might find the TOEFL easier. If you are better at real-world communication and prefer varied question types, the IELTS is likely the better choice for you.</p>
 <p class="mb-6 leading-relaxed">Statistically, the two exams are calibrated to be equal. A score of 100 on the TOEFL is generally considered equivalent to a 7.0 on the IELTS. Your choice should depend on your personal strengths rather than which test is "easier."</p>

